    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. can u go a bit deeper into the mechanism? like how the body actually recruits those neutrophils to the site of infection compared to how lymphocytes hang out in the secondary lymphoid organs or something. just trying to visualize the process better.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Neutrophil recruitment is a rapid, highly localized process involving chemotaxis, where chemical signals at the infection site draw these phagocytic cells out of the bloodstream. Lymphocytes, however, are part of a more nuanced, adaptive response; they are activated and proliferate within secondary lymphoid organs like lymph nodes. This difference reflects the speed and nature of the immune attack—immediate cleanup versus long-term memory and specific targeting.",
      "source": "target",
